{"title_page": "Liu Deyou", "text_new": "{{short description|Chinese politician and translator}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- see Template:Infobox writer -->\n| image      = \n| caption    = \n|name       = Liu Deyou\n|birthname  = \n|birth_date = {{birth year and age|1937|01}}  \n|birth_place= [[Dalian]], [[Liaoning]], [[Republic of China (1912-1949)|China]]\n|death_date = <!--  {{death date and age|}} or {{death year and age| }} -->\n|death_place= \n|residence  = [[Beijing]], China\n|occupation = Politician, translator\n|nationality= Chinese\n| language   = [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]]\n| period     = \n| genre      = \n| subject    = \n| movement   = \n| notableworks=  \n|spouse     = <!--  {{marriage||}}  -->\n|children   = \n|parents    = \n|relations  = \n|website    = \n|signature  = \n|footnotes  =\n| module  = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n|s = {{linktext|\u5218|\u5fb7|\u6709}}\n|t = {{linktext|\u5289|\u5fb7|\u6709}}\n|p = Li\u01d8 D\u00e9y\u01d2u \n|w = \n}}\n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Liu (surname)|Liu]]}}\n\n'''Liu Deyou''' ({{zh|s=\u5218\u5fb7\u6709|t=|p=}}; born January 1937) is a [[Chinese people|Chinese]] politician and translator. \n\n==Biography==\nLiu was born in [[Dalian]], [[Liaoning]] under Japanese rule, in January 1937.<ref name=\"cat\">{{cite news|author= |url=http://paper.people.com.cn/rmrbhwb/html/2010-07/16/content_571245.htm |script-title=zh:\u5218\u5fb7\u6709\u5148\u751f|trans-title=Mr. Liu Deyou |work=people.com.cn |date=2010-07-16 |language=zh}}</ref> In the winter of 1952, Liu was transferred to [[Beijing]] from Dalian and worked in ''People's China'' magazine. He began his translation career during that time.<ref name=\"lion\">{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.ccdy.cn/jiaoliu/201811/t20181121_1398157.htm |script-title=zh:\u5218\u5fb7\u6709\u7684\u7ffb\u8bd1\u4eba\u751f\uff1a\u6587\u7ae0\u5408\u4e3a\u65f6\u800c\u8457 |work=ccdy.cn |date=2018-11-21 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nFrom the mid-1950s to the mid-1960s, he often served as an interpreter when [[Mao Zedong]], [[Zhou Enlai]], [[Chen Yi (marshal)|Chen Yi]], [[Wang Zhen (general)|Wang Zhen]] and [[Guo Moruo]] met with foreign guests or held talks.<ref name=\"tiger\">{{cite news|author= |url=http://news.sohu.com/20070411/n249357826.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5218\u5fb7\u6709\u65b0\u8457\u51fa\u7248 \u62ab\u9732\u62c5\u4efb\u6bdb\u6cfd\u4e1c\u5468\u6069\u6765\u7ffb\u8bd1\u7ecf\u5386(\u56fe) |work=sohu |date=2007-04-11 |language=zh}}</ref> In 1956, he served as simultaneous interpreter at the [[8th National Congress of the Communist Party of China]]. He also visited [[Japan]] with delegations led by Guo Moruo, Wang Zhen and [[Ba Jin]], respectively.<ref name=\"duck\">{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.sohu.com/a/119644071_519778 |script-title=zh:\u98ce\u96e8\u4e1c\u4eac\u8def \u5ed6\u516c\uff08\u5ed6\u627f\u5fd7\uff09\u6d3e\u6211\u505a\u300a\u5149\u660e\u65e5\u62a5\u300b\u9a7b\u65e5\u8bb0\u8005|work=sohu |date=2016-11-22 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nIn 1964, as a reporter of ''[[Guangming Daily]]'', he became one of the first Chinese journalists stationed in Japan. From September 1964 to June 1974, he was the first reporter of ''Guangming Daily'' in [[Tokyo]], Japan. From June 1972 to June 1978, he was the chief journalist of the Tokyo Branch of [[Xinhua News Agency]].<ref name=\"duck\"/> In 1986, he was promoted to vice-minister of the [[Ministry of Culture of the People's Republic of China]].<ref name=\"tiger\"/> \n\nLater, he served as president of the Chinese-Japanese Society and president of the Chinese Cultural Fellowship.\n\nOn November 19, 2018, he was awarded the [[Lifetime Achievement Award in Translation]], one of the most prestigious translation prizes in China.<ref name=\"lion\"/>\n\n==Works==\n* {{cite book |language=zh|author= |script-title=zh:\u98ce\u96e8\u51e0\u661f\u971c\uff1a\u6218\u540e\u4e2d\u65e5\u5173\u7cfb\u4eb2\u5386\u8bb0|trans-title=Storms and Storms: Experiences of Sino-Japanese Relations after World War II |year=2018 |publisher=Joint Publishing |location=Beijing |pages= |isbn=9787108062802 }}\n* {{cite book |language=zh|author= |script-title=zh:\u6211\u4e3a\u9886\u8896\u5f53\u7ffb\u8bd1\uff1a\u4eb2\u5386\u4e2d\u65e5\u9ad8\u5c42\u5f80\u6765|trans-title=I Translate for Leaders: Experience High-level Exchanges Between China and Japan |year=2012 |publisher=Liaoning People's Publishing House |location=Liaoning |pages= |isbn= }}\n* {{cite book |language=ja|author= |script-title=zh:\u96be\u5fd8\u7684\u5c81\u6708|trans-title=Unforgettable Years |year=2007 |publisher=Zhenghai Media Press |location=Beijing |pages= |isbn=9787508511504 }}\n\n==Awards==\n* 23 June 2000 2nd Class, [[Order of the Rising Sun]]<ref name=\"cat\"/>\n\n* 2003 International Exchange Meritorious Person Award<ref name=\"tiger\"/> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liu, Deyou}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Dalian]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Dalian]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China politicians from Liaoning]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of China politicians from Liaoning]]\n[[Category:Japanese\u2013Chinese translators]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chinese politician and translator}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- see Template:Infobox writer -->\n| image      = \n| caption    = \n|name       = Liu Deyou\n|birthname  = \n|birth_date = {{birth year and age|1937|01}}  \n|birth_place= [[Dalian]], [[Liaoning]], [[Republic of China (1912-1949)|China]]\n|death_date = <!--  {{death date and age|}} or {{death year and age| }} -->\n|death_place= \n|residence  = [[Beijing]], China\n|occupation = Politician, translator\n|nationality= Chinese\n| language   = [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]]\n| period     = \n| genre      = \n| subject    = \n| movement   = \n| notableworks=  \n|spouse     = <!--  {{marriage||}}  -->\n|children   = \n|parents    = \n|relations  = \n|website    = \n|signature  = \n|footnotes  =\n| module  = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n|s = {{linktext|\u5218|\u5fb7|\u6709}}\n|t = {{linktext|\u5289|\u5fb7|\u6709}}\n|p = Li\u01d8 D\u00e9y\u01d2u \n|w = \n}}\n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Liu (surname)|Liu]]}}\n\n'''Liu Deyou''' ({{zh|s=\u5218\u5fb7\u6709|t=|p=}}; born January 1937) is a [[Chinese people|Chinese]] politician and translator. \n\n==Biography==\nLiu was born in [[Dalian]], [[Liaoning]] under Japanese rule, in January 1937.<ref name=\"cat\">{{cite news|author= |url=http://paper.people.com.cn/rmrbhwb/html/2010-07/16/content_571245.htm |script-title=zh:\u5218\u5fb7\u6709\u5148\u751f|trans-title=Mr. Liu Deyou |work=people.com.cn |date=2010-07-16 |language=zh}}</ref> In the winter of 1952, Liu was transferred to [[Beijing]] from Dalian and worked in ''People's China'' magazine. He began his translation career during that time.<ref name=\"lion\">{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.ccdy.cn/jiaoliu/201811/t20181121_1398157.htm |script-title=zh:\u5218\u5fb7\u6709\u7684\u7ffb\u8bd1\u4eba\u751f\uff1a\u6587\u7ae0\u5408\u4e3a\u65f6\u800c\u8457 |work=ccdy.cn |date=2018-11-21 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nFrom the mid-1950s to the mid-1960s, he often served as an interpreter when [[Mao Zedong]], [[Zhou Enlai]], [[Chen Yi (marshal)|Chen Yi]], [[Wang Zhen (general)|Wang Zhen]] and [[Guo Moruo]] met with foreign guests or held talks.<ref name=\"tiger\">{{cite news|author= |url=http://news.sohu.com/20070411/n249357826.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5218\u5fb7\u6709\u65b0\u8457\u51fa\u7248 \u62ab\u9732\u62c5\u4efb\u6bdb\u6cfd\u4e1c\u5468\u6069\u6765\u7ffb\u8bd1\u7ecf\u5386(\u56fe) |work=sohu |date=2007-04-11 |language=zh}}</ref> In 1956, he served as simultaneous interpreter at the [[8th National Congress of the Communist Party of China]]. He also visited [[Japan]] with delegations led by Guo Moruo, Wang Zhen and [[Ba Jin]], respectively.<ref name=\"duck\">{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.sohu.com/a/119644071_519778 |script-title=zh:\u98ce\u96e8\u4e1c\u4eac\u8def \u5ed6\u516c\uff08\u5ed6\u627f\u5fd7\uff09\u6d3e\u6211\u505a\u300a\u5149\u660e\u65e5\u62a5\u300b\u9a7b\u65e5\u8bb0\u8005|work=sohu |date=2016-11-22 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nIn 1964, as a reporter of ''[[Guangming Daily]]'', he became one of the first Chinese journalists stationed in Japan. From September 1964 to June 1974, he was the first reporter of ''Guangming Daily'' in [[Tokyo]], Japan. From June 1972 to June 1978, he was the chief journalist of the Tokyo Branch of [[Xinhua News Agency]].<ref name=\"duck\"/> In 1986, he was promoted to vice-minister of the [[Ministry of Culture of the People's Republic of China]].<ref name=\"tiger\"/> \n\nLater, he served as president of the Chinese-Japanese Society and president of the Chinese Cultural Fellowship.\n\nOn November 19, 2018, he was awarded the [[Lifetime Achievement Award in Translation]], one of the most prestigious translation prizes in China.<ref name=\"lion\"/>\n\n==Works==\n* {{cite book |language=zh|author= |script-title=zh:\u98ce\u96e8\u51e0\u661f\u971c\uff1a\u6218\u540e\u4e2d\u65e5\u5173\u7cfb\u4eb2\u5386\u8bb0|trans-title=Storms and Storms: Experiences of Sino-Japanese Relations after World War II |year=2018 |publisher=Joint Publishing |location=Beijing |pages= |isbn=9787108062802 }}\n* {{cite book |language=zh|author= |script-title=zh:\u6211\u4e3a\u9886\u8896\u5f53\u7ffb\u8bd1\uff1a\u4eb2\u5386\u4e2d\u65e5\u9ad8\u5c42\u5f80\u6765|trans-title=I Translate for Leaders: Experience High-level Exchanges Between China and Japan |year=2012 |publisher=Liaoning People's Publishing House |location=Liaoning |pages= |isbn= }}\n* {{cite book |language=ja|author= |script-title=zh:\u96be\u5fd8\u7684\u5c81\u6708|trans-title=Unforgettable Years |year=2007 |publisher=Zhenghai Media Press |location=Beijing |pages= |isbn=9787508511504 }}\n\n==Awards==\n* 23 June 2000 2nd Class, [[Order of the Rising Sun]]<ref name=\"cat\"/>\n\n* 2003 International Exchange Meritorious Person Award<ref name=\"tiger\"/> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liu, Deyou}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:People from Dalian]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Liaoning]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China politicians from Liaoning]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of China politicians from Liaoning]]\n[[Category:Japanese\u2013Chinese translators]]\n", "name_user": "Nlu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u00b1Category:People from Dalian\u2192Category:Politicians from Dalian; \u00b1Category:Writers from Liaoning\u2192Category:Writers from DalianusingHotCat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liu_Deyou"}
